description: Three FPÖ ministers resigned on 8 September 2002 following conflict with the party leader over the governments tax policy.
Freedom Party (FPÖ) ministers joined Future of Austria (BZÖ) on 4 April 2005 and the parliamentary group split into FPÖ and BZÖ members remaining formally one group in parliament.
Liberals resigned over the return of King Leopold.
Liberals resigned on 17 February 1961 following disagreement on tax policies but the request was not accepted by the king.
FDF ministers resigned on 16 January 1980, following conflict over regionalisation,
VU ministers withdrew from cabinet on 29 September 1991 over a dispute on arms trade.
Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) withdrew from cabinet on 29 November 1997, following the Christian Democrats (KDU), over a campaign finance scandal.
Christian Democrats (KDU) withdrew from cabinet on 28 November 1997 over a campaign finance scandal.
Christian Democrats pulled out of government on 30 March 2005, Previously, they demanded the resignation of PM Gross.

Centre Democrats (CD) announced on 20 December 1996 to leave the cabinet over the increased dependence of the cabinet on far left party support but to keep supporting it. The party's ministers resigned on 30 December.
RKP-SFP ministers resigned on 2 July 1957 objecting delays in the government's economic stabilization program.
Centre party ministers resigned on 27 November 1958 over disagreement on policy towards the Soviet Union.
Minister of Foreign Affairs Johan Törngren (RKP-SFP) served as a private person in cabinet. The party is coded at government.fi but not in Müller/Strøm (2000).
All three Social Democratic (TPSL) ministers resigned on 18 October 1963.
Swedish People's Party (RKP-SFP) opposed income and property tax increases leading to the end of the cabinet in December 1963.
SKDL MPs refused to vote for a government bill involvinhg price control relaxation on 17 March 1971 but the three SKDL ministers did not offer to resign.
SKDL opposed government bill to increase defense spending on 30 December 1982.
Toimi Kankaanniemi resigned on 20 June 1994 in opposition to the EU membership agreement.
Greens (VIHR) party group decided to resign from the cabinet opposing plans to build a new nuclear power plant (Reuters).
GB/BHE ministers left party group and joined Christian Democratis (CDU) on 15 July 1955 (guest status until 20 March 1956) (Schindler 1999, 916).
The two ministers of the German Party (DP) left their parliamentary group on 1 July 1960 and later joined the Christian Democrats (CDU).
FDP ministers resigned on 19 November 1962 following the Spiegel scandal but reentered the government on 13 December.
Ministers withdrew from cabinet in conflict over potential tax increases.
Several MPs left the FDP party group and joined the CDU in opposition to the Ostpolitik.
Ministers resigned on 17 September 1982 in conflict over social and tax policies.

Progressives (F) decided to withdraw from government at the beginning of March 1956 over the presence of United States troops in Iceland. It formally withdrew in a letter to the president on 26 March (NYT).
Social Democratic ministers resigned on 9 October 1979.
Socialists (PSI) ministers resigned on 5 August 1982 over an austerity bill announcing the resignation the day before.
Socialist Party (PSI) fostered a cabinet crisis when it announced on 26 March 1991 that Italy needed a new government (NYT).
Northern League (LN) announced on 17 December 1994 to bring down the government through a confidence vote.

description: New party group formed during the legislative term.
LPP withdraws from coaltion on 28 January 2004 after the dismissal of Ainars Slesers as deputy prime minister on 26 January.
LSAP ministers left government after CSV joined a vote of non-confidence against an LSAP minister.

VVD supported a no-confidence vote opposing colonial policy in New Guinea. The vote got no majoriy in parliament but minister of foreign affairs Dirk Stikker resigned a day later leading to the fall of the cabinet.
Socialist ministers resigned on 12 December 1958 following a defeat in parliament on a vote to extend a temporary tax increase.
Party left government in opposition to budget cuts.
Christian Democratic (KVP and ARP) ministers announced their resignation from cabinet on 22 March 1977 leading to the resignation of the entire cabinet.
Christian Democratic (KVP and ARP) ministers announced their resignation from cabinet on 22 March 1977 leading to the resignation of the entire cabinet.
Ministers left cabinet in conflict over budget cuts.
Parliamentary group did not support tax policy decision of cabinet ('reiskostenforfait').
Party group withdrew coalition support over the Ayaan Hirsi Ali identity fraud controversy.
New Zealand First leader Winston Peters was dismissed on 14 August 1998 following disagreement over a privatization issue.
Party opposed relaxing laws for limits on foreign ownership leading to the fall of the cabinet.
Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) splinter group formed 1 April 2004.
CDS ministers resigned on 24 July 1978 in conflict over agricultural and health policies.
Party quit coalition on 14 June 1985 over economic policy.
KDH withdrew from government on 6 February 2006 over religious issues and the three KDH minsters resigned two days later.
Party withdrew from coalition on 8 April 1994 after the dismissal of Defence Minister Janez Jansa on 28 March.
SLS ministers announced to resign on 15 April 2000 to form a new coalition.
SLS ministers resigned on 7 April 2004 due to pressure by Prime Minister Rop and following a controversial vote.
Moderate (Moderaterna) ministers left cabinet on 8 May 1982 in disagreement over a tax reform agreement of coalition partners with the Social Democratic Party.
Ministers left party and parliamentary group (Peter-Michael Diestel on 30 June 1990 and Hans-Wilhelm Ebeling on 2 July).
Party joined CDU on 5 August 1990.
Party withdrew from coalition on 19 August 1990 and its ministers resigned a day later.
Parliamentary group (DFP, LDP, FDP, [BFD]; NDPD) with 23 seats. It withdrew from the coalition on 24 July 1990 but its ministers remained in cabinet.
Ministers were fired on 21 May 2009 after disputes over budget cuts and unemployment benefits.

SRP withdrew temporarily from the coalition after PM Kaczyński dismissed deputy prime minister and SRP party leader Andrzej Lepper on 22 September 2006. Lepper was re-appointed on 16 October and the coalition continued. 
PM Kaczyński  dismissed Lepper again on 9 July 2007 following corruption allegations. Lepper threatened to withdraw the SRP from government but the party decided to remain in government. On 8 August, the interior minister Janusz Kaczmarek was fired and the coalition ended shortly after.
Free Democrats voted to leave coalition on 26 April 2009 in conflict over social and economic policy.
New Flemish Alliance (NVA) did not have ministers in the cabinet.

description: Party left government in oppostion to foreign policy on Afganistan troop deployments

Zares demanded a cabinet reshuffle, implying a replacement of the prime minister. When its demand were not met it announced on 20 June 2011 that it would leave the coalition and its ministers resigned a week later.
DeSUS council decided to leave coalition on 9 May 2011 following disagreement over pension reforms. Last DeSUS minister Roko Zarnic left party on 19 May 2011.
Party left coalition on 22 October 1957 in conflict over a planned pension reform.
Conservatives (ÖVP) withdrew from coalition on 8 July 2008 and asked to call early election. Their ministers remained in office until the next cabinet formed.
Green party announced in November 2010 that it would leave cabinet after passing an important finance bill. They withdrew from the cabinet on 23 January 2011.
Progressive Democrat (PD) minister remained in cabinet as independent when party disbanded and formally dissolved on 20 November 2009.
Communist withdrew from cabinet and its minister Karl Altmann resigned on 20 November 1947 over economic issues.

description: Movement for Social Democracy (EDEK) decided to withdraw from government on 8 February 2010 in disagreement over President Christiofias' strategy on the Cyprus conflict. Its ministers resigned on 2 March (Cyprus Mail).
All PSD cabinet minsters resigned on 1 October 2010 in protest against the dismissal of interior minister Dan Nica by PM Boc.
Conservative Party withdrew from coalition on 3 December 2006 and its ministers resigned
Democratic Party (PD) ministers resigned on 29 January 1998 in protest over the slow reform process.
Christian Democratic ministers threatened to resign on 13 December 1999 leading to the dismissal of PM Vasile.
Republicans (UDR) threatened to resign in mid December over a proposal of PM D'Alema to add the Democrats (ID) to the coaliton (AFP).

description: PM Popescu-Tariceanu fired ministers from the Democratic Party following conflict with president Băsescu.
Party withdrew from coaliton on 26 January 1996 after PM Drnovsek called for the resignation of Economic Minister Maks Tajnikar without consulting the party.
Party withdrew from coalition on 22 April 2010 in conflict over voting rights in a bilingual district near Brussels.
Party withdrew from coalition on 17 March 2010 in conflict over economic policy.
The SDP withdrew from the coalition after PM Hatoyama dismissed SDP chief Mizuho Fukushima as consumer affairs minister on 30 May 2010 following conflict over a US military base.
Free Democratic (FDP) party group split on 23 February 1956. Its ministers remained in office and formed the Free People's Party (FVP) party group.
Free People's Party (FVP) parliamentary group was created as a split-off from the Free People's Party (FVP) and included four cabinet members.
Deputy PM Karolina Peake and other ministers withdrew from VV party group on 17 April 2012 and formed a new group.
Freedom and Solidarity (SaS) abstained in a vote of confidence on 11 October 2011 leading to the fall of the cabinet.
Democratic Party (DIKO) withdrew from cabinet and its ministers handed in their resignation on 27 July 2011 (Cyprus Mail).
All four Popular Orthodox Rally (LAOS) ministers resigned on 10 February 2012 following disagreement over a bailout bill.
Finnish People's Party (SK) opposed income and property tax increases leading to the end of the cabinet in December 1963.
Italian Socialist Party (SDI) threatened to resign in mid December and called for the resignation of PM D'Alema (AFP).
Gabriel Oprea, an independent MP and Minister of Defence since 23 December 2009 (EJPR), was a founding member of the UNPR which formed on 2 May 2010 (Agerpres).
Democratic Reform Party (DRP) with no seats in the lower house but 11 seats in the upper house.
